dst eat to live  not live to eat.', 20928, 0), (400440, 'The nearer the bone  the sweeter the meat.', 41936, 0), (400441, 'I want every peasant to have a chicken in his pot on Sundays.', 63352, 0), (400442, 'When I demanded of my friend what viands he preferred  He quoth: "A large cold bottle  and a small hot bird!"', 13960, 0), (400443, 'Let us eat and drink  for tomorrow we shall die.', 5587, 0), (400444, 'For a man seldom thinks with more earnestness of anything than he does of his dinner.', 2087, 0), (400445, 'Man shall not live by bread alone', 21732, 0), (400446, 'The way to a man''s heart is through his stomach.', 63353, 0), (400447, 'Better is a dinner of herbs where love is  than a stalled ox and hatred therewith.', 33, 0), (400448, 'He hath eaten me out of house and home.', 13, 0), (400449, 'They say fingers were made before forks  and hands before knives.', 995, 0), (400450, 'Bread is the staff of life.', 995, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (400451, 'Buy not what you want  but what you have need of  what you do not want is dear at a farthing.', 33, 0), (400452, 'He who will not economize will have to agonize.', 819, 0), (400453, 'After order and liberty  economy is one of the highest essentials of a free government.... Economy is always a guarantee of peace.', 4110, 0), (400454, 'Beware of little expenses  a small leak will sink a great ship.', 1077, 0), (400455, 'No man is rich whose expenditure exceeds his means  and no one is poor whose incomings exceed his outgoings.', 62823, 0), (400456, 'Have more than thou showest  Speak less than thou knowest.', 13, 0), (400457, 'A gentleman need not know Latin  but he should at least have forgotten it.', 63354, 0), (400458, 'A one-book man is either a slow learner or an ill-equipped teacher.', 63355, 0), (400459, 'Arrogance  pedantry  and dogmatism are the occupational diseases of those who spend their lives directing the intellects of the young.', 63356, 0), (400460, 'Creatures whose main spring is curiosity will enjoy the accumulating of fact  far more than the pausing at times to reflect on those facts.', 62206, 0), (400461, 'Good teaching is l/4th preparation and 3/4ths theatre.', 15819, 0), (400462, 'He who would learn to fly one day must first learn to stand and walk and run and climb and dance  one cannot fly into flying.', 11, 0), (400463, 'Learning makes a man fit company for himself.', 1348, 0), (400464, 'I forget what I was taught. I only remember what I have learnt.', 3418, 0), (400465, 'I pay the School Master  but ''tis the school boys that educate my son.', 760, 0), (400466, 'If you educate a man you educate a person  but if you educate a woman  you educate a family.', 63357, 0), (400467, 'If you hit a pony over the nose at the outset of your acquaintance  he may not love you but he will take a deep interest in your movements ever afterwards.', 843, 0), (400468, 'On many American campuses